<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n38158c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n38" href="#n38158c">N38 (VI.B.32)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n38all.htm#n38158c"> 158(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Tho u(g)s t ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Another rubric in the same papyrus says that the text was cut upon the alabaster plinth of a statue of Menkaur (Mycerinus), a king of the IVth dynasty, and that the letters were inlaid with lapis lazuli. The plinth was found by Prince Herutataf, <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> a son of King Khufu (Cheops), who carried it off to his king and exhibited it as a &ldquo;most wonderful&rdquo; thing. This composition was greatly reverenced, for it &ldquo;would make a man victorious upon earth and in the Other World; it would ensure him a safe and free passage through <mark>the Tuat</mark> (Under World); it would allow him to go in and to go out, and to take at any time any form he pleased; it would make his soul to flourish, and would prevent him from dying the <font color="green">[second]</font> death.&rdquo; <small> E.A. Wallis Budge, <a name="BOD2" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BOD2"><cite title="source">The Book of the Dead</cite></a> (1920) 4</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
